ints under the powerful lights of the depot. With its aerodynamic nose-cone and sleek racing-green carriages, the machine stretches into the far distance.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;This is a very different train to the 40-year old trains it&rsquo;s replacing,&rdquo; says Sam Fisk from manufacturer Hitachi, and our guide to the North Star depot near London&rsquo;s Paddington Station. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve imported technology from Japan and our design centre has made sure the train is shaped so it cuts through the air.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome 200 of these Class 800 hybrid units &ndash; capable of running on both overhead power and diesel &ndash; will eventually replace Britain&rsquo;s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fav\u002Fuk-36188805\u002Fthe-high-speed-train-or-intercity-125-is-celebrating-its-40th-year-of-operation\"\u003E40-year-old High Speed Trains\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. They recently made their debut on the line between London and the west of England and will soon be rolled out on the East Coast Main Line to Scotland. That line is a route made famous by world record-breaking steam engines such as the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.flyingscotsman.org.uk\u002F\"\u003EFlying Scotsman\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.railwaymuseum.org.uk\u002Fwhat-was-on\u002Fmallard-75\"\u003E126 mile-an-hour Mallard\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180921-the-robotic-hand-that-rocks-the-cradle\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWould you use a self-rocking cradle?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20180427-why-analogue-design-still-endures\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhy analogue design still endures\u0