door opening by itself.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAh, yes&hellip; the self-opening toilet door. Anyone who has ever used a British train toilet has almost certainly experienced the excruciating horror and embarrassment of the automatic door slowly rolling open for fellow passengers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-how-to-build-a-better-train-toilet-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"I can&rsquo;t understand why the design is so difficult and complicated &ndash; Christian Wolmar","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-how-to-build-a-better-train-toilet-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe problem is down to the design of the buttons, and complicated instructions (in English only), requiring users to press one button to close the door and then another to lock it. To make things even more confusing, the switches are often back to front.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut this isn&rsquo;t the only issue with train toilet design&hellip;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-how-to-build-a-better-train-toilet-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06ndmkz"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-how-to-build-a-better-train-toilet-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;They tend to have a completely unfathomable system for the sink &ndash; the water comes out, air comes out and soap comes out all from different bits hidden under a shelf,&rdquo; says Wolmar. &ldquo;Inevitably you turn on the hot air before the water - I can&rsquo;t understand why the design is so difficult and complicated.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s issues like this that the designers of the new high-speed trains were told to address. With the trains commissioned almost 10 years ago, they&rsquo;ve had plenty of time to get it right.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The government set the specifications and one of the feedbacks was that the standard of the toilets had to be raised from the earlier fleets,&rdquo; says Fisk. &ldquo;We built a wooden mock-up of the whole train and have had more than 200 groups of passengers on board to give us feedback &ndash; then we went to the factory and built the real trains based on what they said.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESo, did the people get what they asked for? BBC Future decided to put this &ldquo;better&rdquo; train toilet to the test.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-how-to-build-a-better-train-toilet-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"We&rsquo;ve made sure the locking system is a lever and you have to push that lever to the right &ndash; Sam Fisk","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-how-to-build-a-better-train-toilet-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EEach train has five toilets on board &ndash; three are similar in size to aircraft toilets and two are designed to fit a wheelchair and include a fold-down baby changing bench. We chose to investigate one of those.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst impressions are good - the toilet is spacious, clean and well-lit, with grey and cream walls. It even has inset wooden panels and two coat hooks.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We made sure that we had wheelchair users come in here, you can turn a wheelchair, we also had people with guide dogs and people with babies,&rdquo; says Fisk. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s really important that the spaces and angles are right.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181008-how-to-build-a-better-train-toilet-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06ndm3k"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F201